%I A396893 #5 Jun 09 2026 10:11:45
%S A396893 1,1,1,3,23,794,113526,47588574,43827996328
%N A396893 Number of unlabeled maximal 6-degenerate graphs on n vertices.
%C A396893 A graph is d-degenerate if every induced subgraph has minimum degree at most d. It is maximal d-degenerate if by adding any edge the property of being d-degenerate is lost.
%C A396893 Maximal d-degenerate graphs can be obtained from d-dimensional 0-extensions starting with the complete graph on d vertices. A d-dimensional 0-extension of a graph adds a new vertex and connects it to d existing vertices.
%C A396893 Maximal d-degenerate graphs are exactly those minimally d-rigid graphs obtained purely from d-dimensional 0-extensions. A graph G is d-rigid, if every generic realization p in dimension d yields a framework (G,p) that is infinitesimally d-rigid; i.e., all its infinitesimal flexes are trivial. It is minimally d-rigid if it is d-rigid but looses this property upon deletion of any edge. If the original graph is minimally d-rigid, so is the graph obtained from the 0-extension.
%H A396893 Allan Bickle, <a href="https://doi.org/10.20429/tag.2024.000105">A Survey of Maximal k-degenerate Graphs and k-Trees</a>, Theory and Applications of Graphs 0(1), Article 5, 2024.
%H A396893 Matteo Gallet, Georg Grasegger, Matthias Himmelmann and Jan Legerský, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3815171">PyRigi -- a general-purpose Python package for the rigidity and flexibility of bar-and-joint frameworks</a>, ACM Transactions on Mathematical Software, 2026.
%H A396893 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18570095">Dataset of minimally d-rigid graphs obtained from 0-extensions</a>, 2026.
%H A396893 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7457820">RigiComp - A Mathematica package for computational rigidity of graphs</a>, 2022.
%H A396893 Martin Larsson, <a href="https://github.com/martinkjlarsson/nauty-laman-plugin">Nauty Laman plugin</a>
%H A396893 PyRigi Developers, <a href="https://pyrigi.github.io/PyRigi/math/rigidity.html">Rigidity Theory</a>, 2025.
%H A396893 Walter Whiteley, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/conm/197">Some matroids from discrete applied geometry</a>, 1996.
%e A396893 The complete graph on seven vertices is the result of a 6-dimensional 0-etxension on the complete graph on six vertices. A 6-dimensional 0-extension from this graph yields a complete graph on eight vertices with one edge removed. There are three graphs that can be obtained from the previous one by adding a new vertex and connecting it to 6 of the existing vertices.
